{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: System Identification and Component Roles",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between a TN-C-S earthing system and the specific roles of the earthing conductor and CPC in the ADS process.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To achieve Automatic Disconnection of Supply (ADS), the earthing system and the individual components must work as a continuous loop. In modern UK housing, we often see systems where the supplier's neutral and earth are combined in the street but separated at the consumer's intake terminal.",
      "For ADS to function, every part of the path must be correctly identified and connected. A fault in a toaster, for example, relies on the internal circuit wiring and the main link to the supplier's earth to ensure the circuit breaker trips instantly."
    ],
    "questionText": "A modern housing estate is supplied by a system where the neutral and earth are combined in the street but separated at the intake. Identify this specific earthing system type and explain the distinct roles of the 'earthing conductor' versus the 'CPC' in ensuring the protective device can trip during a fault.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The system is TN-C-S (or PME).",
      "The earthing conductor connects the Main Earthing Terminal (MET) to the supplier's earth terminal (the means of earthing).",
      "The CPC (Circuit Protective Conductor) connects the metal parts of the equipment/circuit to the MET.",
      "Together they create the path for fault current to flow and trip the protective device."
    ],
    "hint": "Remember that 'C' stands for combined and 'S' for separate. For the conductors, think about which one stays within the circuit and which one connects the whole house to the supplier's earth."
  }
}

